"Hazell S.P., Neve B.P., Groutides C., Douglas A.E., Blackburn T.M., Bale J.S.","Hyperthermic aphids: Insights into behaviour and mortality",2010,"Journal of Insect Physiology","56","2",,"123","131",,,10.1016/j.jinsphys.2009.08.022,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-74449092460&partnerID=40&md5=a6abda6f4cdecc28664fa60879688202","School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham, B15 2TT, United Kingdom; Department of Entomology, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853, United States; Institute of Zoology, ZSL, Regent's Park, London, NW1 4RY, United Kingdom","Hazell, S.P., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham, B15 2TT, United Kingdom; Neve, B.P., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham, B15 2TT, United Kingdom; Groutides, C., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham, B15 2TT, United Kingdom; Douglas, A.E., Department of Entomology, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853, United States; Blackburn, T.M., Institute of Zoology, ZSL, Regent's Park, London, NW1 4RY, United Kingdom; Bale, J.S., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham, B15 2TT, United Kingdom","Although the impact of warming on winter limitation of aphid populations is reasonably well understood, the impacts of hot summers and heat wave events are less clear. In this study, we address this question through a detailed analysis of the thermal ecology of three closely related aphid species: Myzus persicae, a widespread, polyphagous temperate zone pest, Myzus polaris, an arctic aphid potentially threatened by climate warming, and, Myzus ornatus, a glasshouse pest that may benefit from warming. The upper lethal limits (ULT50) and heat coma temperatures of the aphid species reared at both 15 and 20 °C did not differ significantly, suggesting that heat coma is a reliable indicator of fatal heat stress. Heat coma and CTmax were also measured after aphids were reared at 10 and 25 °C for one and three generations. The extent of the acclimation response was not influenced by the number of generations. Acclimation increased CTmax with rearing temperature for all species. The acclimation temperature also influenced heat coma; this relationship was linear for M. ornatus and M. polaris but non-linear for M. persicae (increased tolerance at 10 and 25 °C). Bacteria known generically as secondary symbionts can promote thermal tolerance of aphids, but they were not detected in the aphids studied here. Assays of optimum development temperature were also performed for each species. All data indicate that M. persicae has the greatest tolerance of high temperatures. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Agriculture; Aphid; Climate warming; CTmax; Heat coma; Upper lethal limits","acclimation; agricultural development; aphid; global warming; high temperature; population distribution; summer; temperature tolerance; animal; animal behavior; aphid; article; bacterial phenomena and functions; ecosystem; growth, development and aging; microbiology; physiology; symbiosis; temperature; Animals; Aphids; Bacterial Physiological Phenomena; Behavior, Animal; Ecosystem; Symbiosis; Temperature; Aphididae; Bacteria (microorganisms); Myzus; Myzus ornatus; Myzus persicae",,,,,,"Addo-Bediako, A., Chown, S.L., Gaston, K.J., Thermal tolerance, climatic variability and latitude (2000) Proceedings of the Royal Society of London Series B-Biological Sciences, 267, pp. 739-745; Adler, L.S., De Valpine, P., Harte, J., Call, J., Effects of long-term experimental warming on aphid density in the field (2007) Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 80, pp. 156-168; Bale, J.S., Masters, G.J., Hodkinson, I.D., Awmack, C., Bezemer, T.M., Brown, V.K., Butterfield, J., Whittaker, J.B., Herbivory in global climate change research: direct effects of rising temperature on insect herbivores (2002) Global Change Biology, 8, pp. 1-16; Beckett, S.J., Morton, R., Darb